body:
@tqchen I tried what you suggested and even tried without cuDNN and I am still getting this error

what():  [19:45:57] src/engine/./threaded_engine.h:295: [19:45:57] ./mshadow/mshadow/./tensor_gpu-inl.h:44: Check failed: e == cudaSuccess CUDA: out of memory

NOTE - I installed mxnet today from github. This error only comes when I try to use image of size bigger than 64,64.

Ok, I narrowed down the problem. The problem is in storage.cc. It uses `PooledStorageManager`, which, in fact, does do caching. It has some logic to prevent OOM, but there are two issues with it:
1. The threshold is hardcoded to 4GB. It is hardcoded to an extent that it is a template argument, not even a variable :) My videocard has 2GB of memory, so obviously it OOMs way before the threshold is reached.
2. The threshold check is broken anyway. Look at this code from `pooled_storage_manager.h`:

```
    if (kThreshold <= used_memory_) {
      ReleaseAll();
    }
    used_memory_ += size;
    return DeviceStorage::Alloc(size);
```

It compares used memory with the threshold before it increases the memory used, so if an allocation exceeds 4GB, it will go through, and cause OOM even if I do have 4GB. The logic should be:

```
    used_memory_ += size;
    if (kThreshold <= used_memory_) {
      ReleaseAll();
    }
    return DeviceStorage::Alloc(size);
```

For a fix I suggest to make the threshold a variable instead of a template argument, and set it to the total GPU memory. I would also suggest to add an environment variable that allows changing it.

For my purposes for now I just reduced the threshold to 1.5GB in the source code.

Also, I don't know if you care about windows, but on windows this line will overflow:

```
 4096 * 1024 * 1024ul
```

Because unsigned long is 32 bit. Should be `ull` instead.

Ideally, the complete serialization solution is cleaner, but might require a bit of thought. The second approach can be hidden using some kind of decorator patterns.

``` python
import mx.kvstore # remove block check here

class MyOpt(xx):
    pass

# block in this decorator
@mx.dist.main
def main():
    # other code
```
